<div id="review_1707662052" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1707662052" />
    <a title="Joe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30725889-joe"><img alt="Joe" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1707662052?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe" href="/user/show/30725889-joe">Joe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30725889-joe?shelf=2016">2016</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30725889-joe?shelf=disturbing">disturbing</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30725889-joe?shelf=holidays">holidays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1707662052" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8028026334646321641">We know very little about the narrator. He is a paranoid loner who works with computers from his home. He is a war veteran. The novel begins with him contemplating the best way to kill himself. He worries that he will back out of the decision in the last second and end up either paralysed or at &apos;the funny farm&apos;. A gun is the best way to do it, he decides. However, there is a glitch with the computer system at the gun shop, and our narrator is forced to wait a few days before he can receive the f</span>
  <span id="freeText8028026334646321641" style="display:none">We know very little about the narrator. He is a paranoid loner who works with computers from his home. He is a war veteran. The novel begins with him contemplating the best way to kill himself. He worries that he will back out of the decision in the last second and end up either paralysed or at 'the funny farm'. A gun is the best way to do it, he decides. However, there is a glitch with the computer system at the gun shop, and our narrator is forced to wait a few days before he can receive the firearm. During this waiting period he has an epiphany. He will not kill himself. He will kill those who he perceives to be bad, and thus, deserve to die more than him. He finds that his life now has a purpose, and he has a reason to get out of bed in the morning. <br /><br /><i>Waiting Period</i> was Selby's final novel and it is his one novel that I would urge first-time Selby readers to avoid, because it would be a bad first impression. That is not to say that it is a bad novel. On the contrary, it is highly disturbing - I would tentatively describe it as being a somewhat tamer version of <i>The Room</i>, very tentatively however! The narrator's psychosis and self-appointed crusade is highly unsettling to read and once again demonstrates Selby's talent for getting right into the dark recesses of the mind and exposing them. At the same time, <i>Waiting Period</i> is underwhelming and feels unpolished. I wonder if Selby's life-long illnesses had simply caught up with him at this stage, and perhaps he had rushed through this one in order to have it finished. I could label <i>Waiting Period</i> a disappointing end to Selby's career and life, but that seems extremely harsh and disrespectful to the man. What ultimately diminishes the quality of this work is that it is invariably overshadowed by the giants of his oeuvre.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8028026334646321641" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


