<div id="review_682355287" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/682355287" />
    <a title="Gerard  Perry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4644141-gerard-perry"><img alt="Gerard  Perry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307499212p2/4644141.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/682355287?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gerard  Perry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gerard  Perry" href="/user/show/4644141-gerard-perry">Gerard  Perry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4644141-gerard-perry?shelf=morbidity">morbidity</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer682355287" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14915387918031626209">Reading this was a chore. I finished the first 300 pages of Les Miserables more quickly than the first 30 pages of this novel, which is excruciatingly tedious. I suppose the narration mirrors the solipsism and pointlessness of the protagonist&apos;s life by design, but that doesn&apos;t make this book any more appealing. Selby took a concept that should be fascinating, i.e. a suicidal, non-ideological, methodical urban terrorist for the modern era, and turned out a plodding dirge. <br/><br/>It&apos;s not so much that th</span>
  <span id="freeText14915387918031626209" style="display:none">Reading this was a chore. I finished the first 300 pages of Les Miserables more quickly than the first 30 pages of this novel, which is excruciatingly tedious. I suppose the narration mirrors the solipsism and pointlessness of the protagonist's life by design, but that doesn't make this book any more appealing. Selby took a concept that should be fascinating, i.e. a suicidal, non-ideological, methodical urban terrorist for the modern era, and turned out a plodding dirge. <br /><br />It's not so much that the main character is unlikable-literature is filled with characters who are loathsome yet compelling-but that he is completely and utterly uninteresting. I can't explain why Selby is such a beloved author, especially among my friends and family, based upon this work. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14915387918031626209" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


